🛠️ Step 1: Configure Git for Future Use
Ensure your Git configuration is set up to use Yahoo's SMTP server for sending emails:​

bash
Copy
Edit
git config --global sendemail.smtpServer smtp.mail.yahoo.com
git config --global sendemail.smtpServerPort 465
git config --global sendemail.smtpUser your-email@yahoo.com
git config --global sendemail.smtpEncryption ssl
git config --global sendemail.smtpsPass your-app-password
Replace your-email@yahoo.com with your actual Yahoo email address and your-app-password with the app-specific password you generated earlier.​

✉️ Step 2: Sending Patches
When you're ready to send a patch, follow these steps:​

Generate the Patch:

bash
Copy
Edit
git format-patch -1 HEAD
Send the Patch:

bash
Copy
Edit
git send-email --to=linux-staging@vger.kernel.org 0001-your-patch-name.patch
Replace 0001-your-patch-name.patch with the actual filename generated by git format-patch.

🔄 Step 3: Updating App Passwords
If you change your Yahoo account password, you'll need to generate a new app-specific password:​
Kinsta®
+2
Yahoo Help
+2
Yahoo Help
+2

Generate a New App Password:

Sign in to your Yahoo Account Security page.

Click "Generate app password".

Select "Other App" and enter a name (e.g., "Git Send Email").

Click "Generate password" and note the new password.​
Yahoo Help
+1
Yahoo Help
+1

Update Git Configuration:

bash
Copy
Edit
git config --global sendemail.smtpsPass new-app-password
Replace new-app-password with the new app-specific password.

⚙️ Optional: Disable Confirmation Prompts
To avoid confirmation prompts when sending emails, you can disable them:​

bash
Copy
Edit
git config --global sendemail.confirm never
This setting will automatically send emails without asking for confirmation.​

If you have any further questions or need assistance with other aspects of contributing to the Linux kernel, feel free to ask!





=====commands====

> git checkout your-branch-name
> git format-patch -1 HEAD
> git send-email --to=linux-staging@vger.kernel.org 0001-your-patch-name.patch
